  "question_type": "choice",
  "question": "You are designing a search module for a static array of N elements. You must handle Q queries where Q ≫ N. The environment restricts auxiliary space to O(1) and mandates strict worst-case time guarantees per query. Which approach minimizes total execution time?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Linear Search, avoiding preprocessing overhead while satisfying space constraints.",
    "B": "Hash Table, providing constant-time average lookups suitable for high query volumes.",
    "C": "In-place Sort followed by Binary Search, balancing space limits with worst-case efficiency.",
    "D": "In-place Sort followed by Linear Search, optimizing data locality without extra space."
  },
  "correct_answer": "C",
  "explanation": "To minimize total runtime under the given constraints, we must evaluate each option against space, worst-case time, and query volume:\n\n1. **Linear Search (Option A)**: Uses O(1) space and has O(N) worst-case query time. Total time is O(Q·N). While it meets space and worst-case constraints, it is inefficient for Q ≫ N.\n2. **Hash Table (Option B)**: Typically requires O(N) auxiliary space to build the table from an array, violating the space constraint. Additionally, standard hashing offers O(1) average time but O(N) worst-case time due to collisions, violating the worst-case guarantee.\n3. **In-place Sort + Binary Search (Option C)**: An in-place sort (e.g., Heapsort) uses O(1) auxiliary space (or O(log N) stack for Quicksort), satisfying the space constraint. Binary search guarantees O(log N) worst-case query time. Total time is O(N log N + Q log N). Since Q ≫ N, the amortized cost per query is logarithmic, making this the optimal choice.\n4. **In-place Sort + Linear Search (Option D)**: Sorting does not improve the worst-case time complexity of linear search, which remains O(N) per query. This yields no benefit over Option A.\n\nTherefore, Option C is the only approach that satisfies all constraints while optimizing for many queries.",
  "verification_code": null
}
